President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 2015 as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of addressing the issue of sexual assault in America and emphasizes the need for everyone to take action against this injustice. He acknowledges that sexual assault not only harms individuals but also weakens the foundation of the nation. The President mentions the progress made over the years in changing the way people think about sexual misconduct and ensuring that every person has the right to be free from sexual assault. He also mentions the establishment of the White House Advisor on Violence Against Women and the White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault as steps taken by his administration to address the issue. The President urges all Americans to support survivors of sexual assault and work together to prevent these crimes in their communities.